{"title_page": "Oliver Baldwin, 2nd Earl Baldwin of Bewdley", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name        = The Earl Baldwin of Bewdley\n|image       = Oliverbaldwin.jpg\n|office        = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n |term_start      = 14 December 1947\n |term_end      = 10 August 1958<br/>[[Hereditary peer|Hereditary Peerage]]\n |predecessor       = [[Stanley Baldwin|The 1st Earl Baldwin of Bewdley]]\n |successor       = [[Arthur Baldwin, 3rd Earl Baldwin of Bewdley|The 3rd Earl Baldwin of Bewdley]]\n|office1      = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Paisley (UK Parliament constituency)|Paisley]]\n|term_start1  = 5 July 1945\n|term_end1    = 14 December 1947\n|predecessor1 = [[Joseph Maclay, 2nd Baron Maclay|Joseph Maclay]]\n|successor1   = [[Dudley Jack Barnato Joel]]\n|office2     = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Dudley (UK Parliament constituency)|Dudley]]\n|term_start2 = 30 May 1929\n|term_end2   = 27 October 1931\n|predecessor2= [[Cyril Edward Lloyd]]\n|successor2  = [[Douglas Johnston, Lord Johnston|Douglas Johnston]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1899|3|1|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Astley Hall (Stourport-on-Severn)|Astley Hall, Worcestershire]], England\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|1958|8|10|1899|3|1||df=y}}\n|death_place = [[Mile End]], [[London]], England\n|party       = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|parents     = {{plain list|\n* [[Stanley Baldwin]]\n* [[Lucy Baldwin|Lucy Ridsdale]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Oliver Ridsdale Baldwin, 2nd Earl Baldwin of Bewdley''' (1 March 1899{{space}}\u2013 10 August 1958), known as '''Viscount Corvedale''' from 1937 to 1947, was a British [[socialist]] politician who had a career at political odds with his father, the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] prime minister [[Stanley Baldwin]].\n\nEducated at [[Eton College|Eton]], which he hated, Baldwin left as soon as he could. After serving in the army during the First World War he undertook various jobs, including a brief appointment as an officer in the [[Armenian army]], and wrote journalism and books on a range of topics. He served two terms as a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of Parliament]] between 1929 and 1947.\n\nBaldwin never achieved ministerial office in Britain. His last post was as Governor of the [[Leeward Islands]], from 1948 to 1950.\n\n==Life and career==\n\n===Early years===\nBaldwin was born at [[Astley Hall (Stourport-on-Severn)|Astley Hall, Worcestershire]], the elder son of the businessman [[Stanley Baldwin]] and his wife [[Lucy Baldwin, Countess Baldwin of Bewdley|Lucy]], ''n\u00e9e'' Ridsdale.<ref name=who>[http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U234345 \"Baldwin of Bewdley\"], ''Who Was Who'', Oxford University Press, 2014, retrieved 4 August 2015 {{subscription}}</ref> Baldwin senior was elected a Conservative [[Member of Parliament|MP]] in 1908, and rose within fifteen years to become prime minister. He sent his son to [[Eton College]], where the boy failed to fit in. He hated what he saw as the school's snobbery and cruelty,<ref name=lycett>Lycett, Andrew, \"[http://www.newstatesman.com/node/147618 \"An average MP; Oliver Baldwin: a life of dissent, by Christopher J Walker\"], ''[[New Statesman]]'', London. 29 March 2004.</ref> and to his teachers he appeared to be \"full of silliness, egotism, un-divine discontent, contempt for others (and of course for authority, discipline, tradition etc)\".<ref>Lyttelton and Hart-Davis, letter of 13 August 1958, pp. 115\u2013116</ref> His ''Who's Who'' entry states that he was educated \"in football at Eton; in other things, beginning to learn\".<ref>Who's Who, 1938, page 726</ref> He was keen to leave school and join the army to fight in the First World War,<ref>Walker, p. 22</ref> and was commissioned in the [[Irish Guards]] in June 1917.<ref name=times>\"Obituary \u2013 Earl Baldwin of Bewdley\", ''The Times'', London. 12 August 1958. p. 8</ref> He did not join the fighting in France until June 1918,<ref>Walker, p. 31</ref> but then distinguished himself by his bravery.<ref name=times/> His war service strengthened his idealism and increasingly socialist views.<ref name=lycett/>\n\n===Post-war and 1920s===\nAfter the war Baldwin served briefly as British Vice-[[Consul (representative)|Consul]] in [[Boulogne]], and then travelled in north Africa. He refused to be supported by his father, and earned a living as a journalist and travel writer. A chance meeting in Alexandria led to an appointment as an infantry instructor in the newly-independent [[First Republic of Armenia|Armenia]], but soon after he took up the post in 1920 the democratic government collapsed and Baldwin was imprisoned by [[Bolshevik]]-backed revolutionaries. He was freed two months later when democracy was restored, but en route back to Britain he was arrested by the Turkish authorities, accused of spying for [[Soviet]] Russia.<ref>Walker, p. 69</ref> He was held for five months, in grim conditions, with execution a constant threat.<ref>Walker, p. 75</ref> He later wrote a book about his experiences, called ''Six Prisons and Two Revolutions''.<ref name=times/>\n\nAfter his release Baldwin returned to Britain, and in 1922 was briefly engaged to Dorothea (\"Doreen\") Arbuthnot, the daughter of a political ally of his father.<ref>Walker, p. 88</ref> Coming to terms with the fact that he was homosexual, Baldwin broke off the engagement, and settled with John \"Johnnie\" Parke Boyle (July 30, 1893 \u2013 February 24, 1969).<ref>Walker, p. 99</ref> <!--PLEASE SEE TALK PAGE HEALTH WARNING ABOUT FICTITIOUS WEB ACCOUNTS OF BALDWIN BEING OUTED IN THE DAILY MAIL. IT DIDN'T HAPPEN--> Described in ''[[New Statesman|The New Statesman]]'' as \"a charming ne'er-do-well\",<ref name=lycett/> Boyle, who was six years older than Baldwin, became his lifelong partner.<ref>Walker, pp. 99\u2013103</ref>  Boyle's family came from [[Oxfordshire]], where he and Baldwin set up home together, living in what the biographer Christopher J Walker describes as \"gentle, amicable, animal-loving, primitive, homosexual socialism\".<ref>Walker, p. 108</ref>\n\n[[File:Stanley Baldwin ggbain.35233.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Baldwin's father, [[Stanley Baldwin|Stanley]] in the 1920s]]\nAt the [[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924 general election]] Baldwin unsuccessfully contested the seat of [[Dudley (UK Parliament constituency)|Dudley]] for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]. By this time his father was leader of the Conservative Party and prime minister, and his son's candidacy attracted press comment.<ref name=times/>  At the [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929 election]] he won Dudley, and served as a [[backbencher|backbench]] supporter of [[Ramsay MacDonald]]'s Labour government, facing his defeated father across the House of Commons. Father and son remained on the warmest personal terms. Oliver's homosexuality was quietly accepted within the family, and in politics he refrained from personally attacking his father.<ref name=lycett/>\n\nLike other young left-wing Labour MPs, Baldwin was critical of MacDonald's insistence on strict financial management and refusal to launch large [[John Maynard Keynes|Keynesian]] public works programmes.<ref name=w150>Walker, pp. 150\u2013151</ref> Early in 1931 Baldwin resigned from the Labour Party and was briefly associated with [[New Party (Oswald Mosley)|Oswald Mosley's New Party]], but soon repudiated Mosley and rejoined Labour.<ref name=w150/> When MacDonald formed the [[First National ministry|National Government]], Stanley Baldwin and the Conservatives joined it; most Labour members, including Oliver Baldwin, did not. The [[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931 general election]] resulted in a landslide win for the National Government and a disaster for Labour. Baldwin was among the casualties, defeated by a Conservative candidate, [[Park Goff|Sir Park Goff]], who won by 19,991 votes to Baldwin's 10,837 at [[Chatham (UK Parliament constituency)|Chatham]].<ref>\"The General Election\", ''The Times'', 28 October 1931, p. 6</ref> Baldwin returned to journalism. In Walker's view, he was better known as a journalist than as a politician, writing anti-[[fascist]] articles in the usually pro-[[appeasement]] [[Harold Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Rothermere|Rothermere]] press during the 1930s.<ref name=lycett/> He also wrote what the reviewer Andrew Lycett calls \"a curious novel called ''The Coming of Aissa'', which emphasised the socialistic leanings of Jesus within an agnostic, Asian, neoplatonic context.\"<ref name=lycett/>\n\n===Later years===\nBaldwin fought [[Paisley (UK Parliament constituency)|Paisley]] at the [[1935 United Kingdom general election|1935 election]], failing to be elected by 389 votes behind the Liberal candidate.<ref>\"The General Election\", ''The Times'', 15 November 1935, p. 8</ref> In 1937 Stanley Baldwin retired from politics and was created Earl Baldwin of Bewdley. As a result, Oliver Baldwin acquired the [[Courtesy titles in the United Kingdom|courtesy title]] Viscount Corvedale, which did not entail membership of the [[House of Lords]]. In 1939 he rejoined the army, becoming a major in the [[Intelligence Corps (United Kingdom)|Intelligence Corps]] and serving in the [[Near East]] and north Africa.<ref name=times/>\n\nAt the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945 general election]], when Labour returned to power under [[Clement Attlee]], Corvedale was elected for Paisley with a majority of 10,330.<ref>\"News in Brief\", ''The Times'', 13 September 1945, p. 2</ref> The Attlee government lacked representation in the House of Lords, which was dominated by Conservative peers. In 1947 Corvedale accepted the prime minister's offer of a peerage, but before he could take his seat his father died and Corvedale was automatically elevated as the second Earl Baldwin. Lycett comments that had it not been for the first earl's death Baldwin father and son would, uniquely, have sat opposite each other in both houses of parliament.<ref name=lycett/>\n\n==== Governor of the Leeward Islands 1948 - 1950 ====\nIn February 1948 Baldwin was appointed Governor and Commander in Chief of the [[Leeward Islands]], a British colonial territory in the [[Caribbean]].<ref>\"Governor of Leeward Islands\", ''The Times'', 9 February 1948, p. 3</ref> Boyle accompanied him, to the disapproval of some of the British establishment in [[Antigua]]. Baldwin arrived in Antigua in March 1948. Partly for this reason, and partly because Baldwin made no secret of his continuing socialist views or his desire for multiracial inclusiveness, he was recalled in 1950.<ref name=\"lycett\" />\n\n==== Death ====\n[[File:Baldwin gravesite.jpg|thumb|Baldwin's tombstone on a hilltop on the island of Antigua.]]\nBaldwin died in [[Mile End Hospital]], London, in 1958. He was unmarried and was succeeded in the earldom and viscountcy by his younger brother [[Arthur Baldwin, 3rd Earl Baldwin of Bewdley|Arthur]].<ref name=times/> His ashes are interred on a hilltop on the island of Antigua.  The stone inscription reads, ''Here lie the ashes of Oliver Ridsdale Second Earl Baldwin of Bewdley, Born March 1899 Died August 1958. Governor, Commander in Chief in and over the Leeward Islands and Vice Admiral of the same 1948 - 1950. He loved the people of these islands. RIP.''{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Books==\n*''Konyetz'': novel published under the pen name Martin Hussingtree, 1924\n*''Six Prisons and Two Revolutions'': memoirs, 1924\n*''Socialism and the Bible'' (English translation of ''Les Principes du catholicisme social en face de l'Ecriture sainte'' by Jean-Samuel Ouvret), 1928\n*''Conservatism and Wealth: A Radical Indictment'' (with Roger Chance), 1929\n*''The Questing Beast: An Autobiography'', 1932\n*''Unborn Son'': political commentary, 1933\n*''The Coming of A\u00efssa: being the life of A\u00efssa ben Yusuf of El Naseerta, otherwise known as Jesus of Nazareth'', 1935\n*''Oasis'': political and social comment, 1936\n:Source: ''Who Was Who''.<ref name=who/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book | last= Lyttleton | first= George | authorlink=George William Lyttelton|author2=[[Rupert Hart-Davis]]|year=1981 | title=Lyttelton/Hart-Davis Letters, Volume 3| location=London | publisher= John Murray| isbn= 978-0-7195-3770-7}}  \n* {{cite book | last= Walker | first= Christopher J| title= Oliver Baldwin: A Life of Dissent | year=2003 | location=London | publisher= Arcadia | isbn= 978-1-900850-86-5 }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-oliver-baldwin | the Earl Baldwin of Bewdley }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[W. R. Macnie]]'''<br />''(acting)''}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Governor of the Leeward Islands]]|years=1948 \u2013 1950}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kenneth Blackburne|Sir Kenneth Blackburne]]}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Cyril Lloyd]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Dudley (UK Parliament constituency)|Member of Parliament for Dudley]]|years= [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929]] \u2013  [[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Dudley Joel]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Joseph Maclay, 2nd Baron Maclay|Joseph Maclay]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Paisley (UK Parliament constituency)|Member of Parliament for Paisley]]|years= [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945]] \u2013 1947 }}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Douglas Johnston, Lord Johnston|Douglas Johnston]]}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stanley Baldwin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Earl Baldwin of Bewdley]]<br>[[Viscount Corvedale]]|years=1947 \u2013 1958|lords=1947}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Arthur Baldwin, 3rd Earl Baldwin of Bewdley|Arthur Baldwin]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Stanley Baldwin}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baldwin, Oliver}}\n[[Category:1899 births|Baldwin of Bewdley, Oliver Baldwin, 2nd Earl]]\n[[Category:1958 deaths|Baldwin of Bewdley, Oliver Baldwin, 2nd Earl]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Governors of the Leeward Islands|Baldwin of Bewdley, Oliver Baldwin, 2nd Earl]]\n[[Category:Children of Prime Ministers of the United Kingdom|Baldwin of Bewdley, Oliver Baldwin, 2nd Earl]]\n[[Category:Earls in the Peerage of the United Kingdom|Baldwin of Bewdley, Oliver Baldwin, 2nd Earl]]\n[[Category:Gay peers]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:Intelligence Corps officers]]\n[[Category:Irish Guards officers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) hereditary peers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Scottish Labour Party MPs]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Paisley constituencies]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:People from Worcestershire]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1929\u20131931]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1945\u20131950]]\n[[Category:LGBT members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT peers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name        = The Earl Baldwin of Bewdley\n|image       = Oliverbaldwin.jpg\n|office        = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n |term_start      = 14 December 1947\n |term_end      = 10 August 1958<br/>[[Hereditary peer|Hereditary Peerage]]\n |predecessor       = [[Stanley Baldwin|The 1st Earl Baldwin of Bewdley]]\n |successor       = [[Arthur Baldwin, 3rd Earl Baldwin of Bewdley|The 3rd Earl Baldwin of Bewdley]]\n|office1      = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Paisley (UK Parliament constituency)|Paisley]]\n|term_start1  = 5 July 1945\n|term_end1    = 14 December 1947\n|predecessor1 = [[Joseph Maclay, 2nd Baron Maclay|Joseph Maclay]]\n|successor1   = [[Dudley Jack Barnato Joel]]\n|office2     = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Dudley (UK Parliament constituency)|Dudley]]\n|term_start2 = 30 May 1929\n|term_end2   = 27 October 1931\n|predecessor2= [[Cyril Edward Lloyd]]\n|successor2  = [[Douglas Johnston, Lord Johnston|Douglas Johnston]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1899|3|1|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Astley Hall (Stourport-on-Severn)|Astley Hall, Worcestershire]], England\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|1958|8|10|1899|3|1||df=y}}\n|death_place = [[Mile End]], [[London]], England\n|party       = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|parents     = {{plain list|\n* [[Stanley Baldwin]]\n* [[Lucy Baldwin|Lucy Ridsdale]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Oliver Ridsdale Baldwin, 2nd Earl Baldwin of Bewdley''' (1 March 1899{{space}}\u2013 10 August 1958), known as '''Viscount Corvedale''' from 1937 to 1947, was a British [[socialist]] politician who had a career at political odds with his father, the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] prime minister [[Stanley Baldwin]].\n\nEducated at [[Eton College|Eton]], which he hated, Baldwin left as soon as he could. After serving in the army during the First World War he undertook various jobs, including a brief appointment as an officer in the Armenian army, and wrote journalism and books on a range of topics. He served two terms as a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of Parliament]] between 1929 and 1947.\n\nBaldwin never achieved ministerial office in Britain. His last post was as Governor of the [[Leeward Islands]], from 1948 to 1950.\n\n==Life and career==\n\n===Early years===\nBaldwin was born at [[Astley Hall (Stourport-on-Severn)|Astley Hall, Worcestershire]], the elder son of the businessman [[Stanley Baldwin]] and his wife [[Lucy Baldwin, Countess Baldwin of Bewdley|Lucy]], ''n\u00e9e'' Ridsdale.<ref name=who>[http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U234345 \"Baldwin of Bewdley\"], ''Who Was Who'', Oxford University Press, 2014, retrieved 4 August 2015 {{subscription}}</ref> Baldwin senior was elected a Conservative [[Member of Parliament|MP]] in 1908, and rose within fifteen years to become prime minister. He sent his son to [[Eton College]], where the boy failed to fit in. He hated what he saw as the school's snobbery and cruelty,<ref name=lycett>Lycett, Andrew, \"[http://www.newstatesman.com/node/147618 \"An average MP; Oliver Baldwin: a life of dissent, by Christopher J Walker\"], ''[[New Statesman]]'', London. 29 March 2004.</ref> and to his teachers he appeared to be \"full of silliness, egotism, un-divine discontent, contempt for others (and of course for authority, discipline, tradition etc)\".<ref>Lyttelton and Hart-Davis, letter of 13 August 1958, pp. 115\u2013116</ref> His ''Who's Who'' entry states that he was educated \"in football at Eton; in other things, beginning to learn\".<ref>Who's Who, 1938, page 726</ref> He was keen to leave school and join the army to fight in the First World War,<ref>Walker, p. 22</ref> and was commissioned in the [[Irish Guards]] in June 1917.<ref name=times>\"Obituary \u2013 Earl Baldwin of Bewdley\", ''The Times'', London. 12 August 1958. p. 8</ref> He did not join the fighting in France until June 1918,<ref>Walker, p. 31</ref> but then distinguished himself by his bravery.<ref name=times/> His war service strengthened his idealism and increasingly socialist views.<ref name=lycett/>\n\n===Post-war and 1920s===\nAfter the war Baldwin served briefly as British Vice-[[Consul (representative)|Consul]] in [[Boulogne]], and then travelled in north Africa. He refused to be supported by his father, and earned a living as a journalist and travel writer. A chance meeting in Alexandria led to an appointment as an infantry instructor in the newly-independent [[First Republic of Armenia|Armenia]], but soon after he took up the post in 1920 the democratic government collapsed and Baldwin was imprisoned by [[Bolshevik]]-backed revolutionaries. He was freed two months later when democracy was restored, but en route back to Britain he was arrested by the Turkish authorities, accused of spying for [[Soviet]] Russia.<ref>Walker, p. 69</ref> He was held for five months, in grim conditions, with execution a constant threat.<ref>Walker, p. 75</ref> He later wrote a book about his experiences, called ''Six Prisons and Two Revolutions''.<ref name=times/>\n\nAfter his release Baldwin returned to Britain, and in 1922 was briefly engaged to Dorothea (\"Doreen\") Arbuthnot, the daughter of a political ally of his father.<ref>Walker, p. 88</ref> Coming to terms with the fact that he was homosexual, Baldwin broke off the engagement, and settled with John \"Johnnie\" Parke Boyle (July 30, 1893 \u2013 February 24, 1969).<ref>Walker, p. 99</ref> <!--PLEASE SEE TALK PAGE HEALTH WARNING ABOUT FICTITIOUS WEB ACCOUNTS OF BALDWIN BEING OUTED IN THE DAILY MAIL. IT DIDN'T HAPPEN--> Described in ''[[New Statesman|The New Statesman]]'' as \"a charming ne'er-do-well\",<ref name=lycett/> Boyle, who was six years older than Baldwin, became his lifelong partner.<ref>Walker, pp. 99\u2013103</ref>  Boyle's family came from [[Oxfordshire]], where he and Baldwin set up home together, living in what the biographer Christopher J Walker describes as \"gentle, amicable, animal-loving, primitive, homosexual socialism\".<ref>Walker, p. 108</ref>\n\n[[File:Stanley Baldwin ggbain.35233.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Baldwin's father, [[Stanley Baldwin|Stanley]] in the 1920s]]\nAt the [[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924 general election]] Baldwin unsuccessfully contested the seat of [[Dudley (UK Parliament constituency)|Dudley]] for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]. By this time his father was leader of the Conservative Party and prime minister, and his son's candidacy attracted press comment.<ref name=times/>  At the [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929 election]] he won Dudley, and served as a [[backbencher|backbench]] supporter of [[Ramsay MacDonald]]'s Labour government, facing his defeated father across the House of Commons. Father and son remained on the warmest personal terms. Oliver's homosexuality was quietly accepted within the family, and in politics he refrained from personally attacking his father.<ref name=lycett/>\n\nLike other young left-wing Labour MPs, Baldwin was critical of MacDonald's insistence on strict financial management and refusal to launch large [[John Maynard Keynes|Keynesian]] public works programmes.<ref name=w150>Walker, pp. 150\u2013151</ref> Early in 1931 Baldwin resigned from the Labour Party and was briefly associated with [[New Party (Oswald Mosley)|Oswald Mosley's New Party]], but soon repudiated Mosley and rejoined Labour.<ref name=w150/> When MacDonald formed the [[First National ministry|National Government]], Stanley Baldwin and the Conservatives joined it; most Labour members, including Oliver Baldwin, did not. The [[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931 general election]] resulted in a landslide win for the National Government and a disaster for Labour. Baldwin was among the casualties, defeated by a Conservative candidate, [[Park Goff|Sir Park Goff]], who won by 19,991 votes to Baldwin's 10,837 at [[Chatham (UK Parliament constituency)|Chatham]].<ref>\"The General Election\", ''The Times'', 28 October 1931, p. 6</ref> Baldwin returned to journalism. In Walker's view, he was better known as a journalist than as a politician, writing anti-[[fascist]] articles in the usually pro-[[appeasement]] [[Harold Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Rothermere|Rothermere]] press during the 1930s.<ref name=lycett/> He also wrote what the reviewer Andrew Lycett calls \"a curious novel called ''The Coming of Aissa'', which emphasised the socialistic leanings of Jesus within an agnostic, Asian, neoplatonic context.\"<ref name=lycett/>\n\n===Later years===\nBaldwin fought [[Paisley (UK Parliament constituency)|Paisley]] at the [[1935 United Kingdom general election|1935 election]], failing to be elected by 389 votes behind the Liberal candidate.<ref>\"The General Election\", ''The Times'', 15 November 1935, p. 8</ref> In 1937 Stanley Baldwin retired from politics and was created Earl Baldwin of Bewdley. As a result, Oliver Baldwin acquired the [[Courtesy titles in the United Kingdom|courtesy title]] Viscount Corvedale, which did not entail membership of the [[House of Lords]]. In 1939 he rejoined the army, becoming a major in the [[Intelligence Corps (United Kingdom)|Intelligence Corps]] and serving in the [[Near East]] and north Africa.<ref name=times/>\n\nAt the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945 general election]], when Labour returned to power under [[Clement Attlee]], Corvedale was elected for Paisley with a majority of 10,330.<ref>\"News in Brief\", ''The Times'', 13 September 1945, p. 2</ref> The Attlee government lacked representation in the House of Lords, which was dominated by Conservative peers. In 1947 Corvedale accepted the prime minister's offer of a peerage, but before he could take his seat his father died and Corvedale was automatically elevated as the second Earl Baldwin. Lycett comments that had it not been for the first earl's death Baldwin father and son would, uniquely, have sat opposite each other in both houses of parliament.<ref name=lycett/>\n\n==== Governor of the Leeward Islands 1948 - 1950 ====\nIn February 1948 Baldwin was appointed Governor and Commander in Chief of the [[Leeward Islands]], a British colonial territory in the [[Caribbean]].<ref>\"Governor of Leeward Islands\", ''The Times'', 9 February 1948, p. 3</ref> Boyle accompanied him, to the disapproval of some of the British establishment in [[Antigua]]. Baldwin arrived in Antigua in March 1948. Partly for this reason, and partly because Baldwin made no secret of his continuing socialist views or his desire for multiracial inclusiveness, he was recalled in 1950.<ref name=\"lycett\" />\n\n==== Death ====\n[[File:Baldwin gravesite.jpg|thumb|Baldwin's tombstone on a hilltop on the island of Antigua.]]\nBaldwin died in [[Mile End Hospital]], London, in 1958. He was unmarried and was succeeded in the earldom and viscountcy by his younger brother [[Arthur Baldwin, 3rd Earl Baldwin of Bewdley|Arthur]].<ref name=times/> His ashes are interred on a hilltop on the island of Antigua.  The stone inscription reads, ''Here lie the ashes of Oliver Ridsdale Second Earl Baldwin of Bewdley, Born March 1899 Died August 1958. Governor, Commander in Chief in and over the Leeward Islands and Vice Admiral of the same 1948 - 1950. He loved the people of these islands. RIP.''{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Books==\n*''Konyetz'': novel published under the pen name Martin Hussingtree, 1924\n*''Six Prisons and Two Revolutions'': memoirs, 1924\n*''Socialism and the Bible'' (English translation of ''Les Principes du catholicisme social en face de l'Ecriture sainte'' by Jean-Samuel Ouvret), 1928\n*''Conservatism and Wealth: A Radical Indictment'' (with Roger Chance), 1929\n*''The Questing Beast: An Autobiography'', 1932\n*''Unborn Son'': political commentary, 1933\n*''The Coming of A\u00efssa: being the life of A\u00efssa ben Yusuf of El Naseerta, otherwise known as Jesus of Nazareth'', 1935\n*''Oasis'': political and social comment, 1936\n:Source: ''Who Was Who''.<ref name=who/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book | last= Lyttleton | first= George | authorlink=George William Lyttelton|author2=[[Rupert Hart-Davis]]|year=1981 | title=Lyttelton/Hart-Davis Letters, Volume 3| location=London | publisher= John Murray| isbn= 978-0-7195-3770-7}}  \n* {{cite book | last= Walker | first= Christopher J| title= Oliver Baldwin: A Life of Dissent | year=2003 | location=London | publisher= Arcadia | isbn= 978-1-900850-86-5 }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Hansard-contribs | mr-oliver-baldwin | the Earl Baldwin of Bewdley }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[W. R. Macnie]]'''<br />''(acting)''}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Governor of the Leeward Islands]]|years=1948 \u2013 1950}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kenneth Blackburne|Sir Kenneth Blackburne]]}}\n{{s-par|uk}