}}\n{{Languages of Italy}}\n{{Romance languages}}\n{{Sicily}}\n\n[[Category:Sicilian language]]\n[[Category:Italo-Dalmatian languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Sicily]]\n[[Category:Languages of Calabria]]\n[[Category:Languages of Apulia]]\n[[Category:Subject\u2013object\u2013verb languages]]\n", "name_user": "AmazingJus", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sicilian_language"}
{"title_page": "Andrea Dovizioso", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian motorcycle racer}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox motorcycle rider\n| name                   = Andrea Dovizioso\n| image= Andrea Dovizioso_talks_to_media.jpg\n| caption                = Dovizioso in 2018\n| nationality            = Italian\n| birth_date             = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1986|3|23}}\n| birth_place            = [[Forlimpopoli]], Italy\n| Current team           = [[Ducati Corse|Ducati Team]]\n| Bike number            = 04\n| website                = [http://www.andreadovizioso.com/ andreadovizioso.com]\n| MotoGP Active years    = {{MGP|2008}}\u2013\n| MotoGP Manufacturers   = [[Ducati]], [[Yamaha Motor Company|Yamaha]], [[Honda]]\n| MotoGP Championships   = 0\n| MotoGP Race Starts     = 215\n| MotoGP Race Wins       = 14\n| MotoGP Podiums         = 60\n| MotoGP Poles           = 7\n| MotoGP Fastest laps    = 11\n| MotoGP Total Points    = 2421\n| MotoGP Last season     = 2019\n| MotoGP Last position   = 2nd (269 pts)\n| 250 Active years       = {{MGP|2005}}\u2013{{MGP|2007}}\n| 250 Manufacturers      = [[Honda]]\n| 250 Championships      = 0\n| 250 Race Starts        = 49\n| 250 Race Wins          = 4\n| 250 Podiums            = 26\n| 250 Poles              = 4\n| 250 Fastest laps       = 8\n| 250 Total Points       = 721\n| 250 Last season        = 2007\n| 250 Last position      = 2nd (260 pts)\n| 125 Active years       = {{MGP|2001}}\u2013{{MGP|2004}}\n| 125 Manufacturers      = [[Honda]], [[Aprilia]]\n| 125 Championships      = 1 ({{MGP|2004}})\n| 125 Race Starts        = 49\n| 125 Race Wins          = 5\n| 125 Podiums            = 15\n| 125 Poles              = 9\n| 125 Fastest laps       = 3\n| 125 Total Points       = 492\n| 125 Last season        = 2004\n| 125 Last position      = 1st (293 pts)\n}}\n\n'''Andrea Dovizioso''' (born 23 March 1986) is a professional motorcycle racer who competes in the [[MotoGP|MotoGP world championship]] for the factory [[Ducati Corse]] team. He won the 125cc World Championship in {{MGP|2004}}. He also finished third in the MotoGP class in {{MGP|2011}} and is a three-time runner-up in the premier class, after finishing second to [[Marc M\u00e1rquez]] in [[2017 MotoGP season|2017]], [[2018 MotoGP season|2018]], and [[2019 MotoGP season|2019]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\nBorn in [[Forlimpopoli]], son of Antonio Dovizioso, a [[Sicily|Sicilian]] motorcycle racer,<ref>[http://www.cinquantamila.it/storyTellerArticolo.php?storyId=5a041123abdfb Lorenzo Longhi, ''Andrea Dovizioso \u00abha gi\u00e0 vinto\u00bb. Parola del padre'', Avvenire, 9 novembre 2017]</ref><ref>[http://ennapress.it/calascibetta-proposta-di-cittadinanza-onoraria-per-il-pilota-di-motogp-andrea-dovizioso.html Calascibetta; proposta di Cittadinanza Onoraria per il pilota di MotoGP Andrea Dovizioso, 28 aprile 2015, Ennapress]</ref> Dovizioso won the 125cc Italian Aprilia Challenge in 2000. In 2001 Dovizioso won the 125cc European Championship and also competed in his first World Championship race at Mugello, in which he retired. During that year he worked with Guido Mancini, a former rider and mechanic who, in the past, had worked with [[Valentino Rossi]] and [[Loris Capirossi]]. A documentary film about Mancini's career, released in 2016 by director Jeffrey Zani, tells the story of that racing season.\n\n===125cc World Championship===\nIn [[2002 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|2002]], Dovizioso competed in the 125cc World Championship with Team Scot Honda, finishing 16th in the final standings. His best results were two 9th places in Le Mans and Donington. He continued with the team in [[2003 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|2003]], finishing 5th in the final standings and achieving four podium finishes. The [[2004 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|2004 season]] saw him pick up five victories and six other podium finishes on his way to winning the championship with 293 points.\n\n===250cc World Championship===\n[[File:Honda NSR250 of Andrea Dovizioso.JPG|thumb|left|Honda NSR250 used by Dovizioso in the 250cc World Championship]]\nIn [[2005 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|2005]] Dovizioso moved to the 250cc class, continuing with Team Scot Honda. The season included five podium finishes and 3rd place in the overall standings. He also won the Rookie of the Year award. In [[2006 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|2006]] he remained with the team, who were now renamed as Humangest Racing. He won two races in Barcelona and Estoril and finished on the podium 11 times. He fought for the championship until the final race of the season, but had to settle for 2nd place behind [[Jorge Lorenzo]]. The [[2007 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|2007 season]] saw him win two races in Istanbul and Donington and challenge once again for the championship, but he finished in 2nd place once again.\n\n===MotoGP World Championship===\n====Honda (2008\u20132011)====\n;2008\n[[File:Andrea Dovizioso at Donington 2008.jpg|thumb|left|Dovizioso at the [[2008 British motorcycle Grand Prix|2008 British Grand Prix]]]]\nOn 15 September 2007, Dovizioso announced that he would be making the move up to the MotoGP class with his existing team in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.crash.net/news_view~cid~6~id~154512.htm|title=Dovizioso confirms MotoGP move|work=Crash.net|publisher=Crash Media Group|date=15 September 2007|accessdate=2 January 2015}}</ref> On his premier class debut, Dovizioso achieved a highly credible fourth place, at the season opener in Qatar, passing [[Valentino Rossi]] on the final lap. Throughout the season, Dovi was one of the most consistent Honda riders, placing 4th and 5th several times, and achieving a 3rd place podium finish at the Malaysian MotoGP at Sepang. Dovizioso finished 5th in the final standings.\n\n;2009\n[[File:Andrea Dovizioso Mugello 2009.jpg|thumb|Dovizioso at the [[2009 Italian motorcycle Grand Prix|2009 Italian Grand Prix]]]]\nFor the {{MGP|2009}} season, Dovizioso became an official [[Repsol Honda]] rider replacing [[Nicky Hayden]] and partnering Spain's [[Dani Pedrosa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.crash.net/motogp/news/81348/1/official-dovizioso-to-repsol-honda.html|title=Official: Dovizioso to Repsol Honda|work=Crash.net|publisher=Crash Media Group|date=26 September 2008|accessdate=2 January 2015}}</ref> In July 2009, Dovizioso won his first race in MotoGP at the [[2009 British motorcycle Grand Prix|British Grand Prix]] in wet conditions at [[Donington Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/motorsport/motorbikes/8169509.stm|title=Shock Donington win for Dovizioso |date=26 July 2009|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=27 July 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090727101047/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/motorsport/motorbikes/8169509.stm| archivedate= 27 July 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Despite otherwise consistent points finishes, Dovizioso ended up with fewer points than in his d\u00e9but season in the class, finishing sixth in the final standings.\n\n;2010\n[[File:Mugello MotoGP podium 2010.jpg|thumb|left|The podium after the [[2010 Italian motorcycle Grand Prix|2010 Italian Grand Prix]]; Dovizioso (right) finished third, behind [[Jorge Lorenzo]] (left), and race-winner [[Dani Pedrosa]] (centre).]]\nDovizioso had a strong start to his second season with the Repsol Honda team, picking up a podium in the season-opening race in [[2010 Qatar motorcycle Grand Prix|Qatar]]. Three more podiums followed early in the year before his results tailed off mid-season. Despite this, Dovizioso consistently collected points finishes and claimed his first pole position in MotoGP at the [[2010 Japanese motorcycle Grand Prix|Japanese Grand Prix]] at [[Twin Ring Motegi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/motorbikes/9054113.stm|title=Andrea Dovizioso takes maiden pole at Japanese MotoGP|work=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=2 October 2010|accessdate=2 October 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101003045956/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/motorbikes/9054113.stm| archivedate= 3 October 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> He went on to finish second in the race after challenging for the race win, equalling his result from the [[2010 British motorcycle Grand Prix|British Grand Prix]]. Dovizioso again finished second in the following race in [[2010 Malaysian motorcycle Grand Prix|Malaysia]]. Dovizioso retired in [[2010 Australian motorcycle Grand Prix|Australia]], and concluded the season with third in [[2010 Portuguese motorcycle Grand Prix|Portugal]] and fifth in [[2010 Valencian Community motorcycle Grand Prix|Valencia]] to finish fifth in the final championship standings.\n\n;2011\n[[File:Andrea Dovizioso 2011 Estoril.jpg|thumb|Dovizioso at the [[2011 Portuguese motorcycle Grand Prix|2011 Portuguese Grand Prix]]]]\nDovizioso remained with Repsol Honda for a third consecutive season in {{MGP|2011}}, riding in a three-bike team alongside [[Casey Stoner]] and Dani Pedrosa. Dovizioso started the season well, with a fourth place in [[2011 Qatar motorcycle Grand Prix|Qatar]] after a race-long battle with [[Marco Simoncelli]]. At [[2011 Spanish motorcycle Grand Prix|Jerez]], Dovizioso experienced severe tyre wear and had to make a tyre change on his way to 12th place in the damp conditions. He took fourth place in [[2011 Portuguese motorcycle Grand Prix|Portugal]], with a late-race pass on [[Valentino Rossi]], before [[2011 French motorcycle Grand Prix|Le Mans]] saw Dovizioso's best performance of the season to that point. Having circulated in sixth for a portion of the race, he was helped by the collision between Pedrosa and Simoncelli, which saw Pedrosa crash out and Simoncelli given a ride-through penalty. He then passed [[Jorge Lorenzo]] and Rossi en route to a second-place finish.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.redbull.com/cs/Satellite/en_INT/Article/Casey-Stoner-wins-French-MotoGP-at-Le-Mans-while-Dani-Pedrosa-suffers-injury-021243016180640 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120911210427/http://www.redbull.com/cs/Satellite/en_INT/Article/Casey-Stoner-wins-French-MotoGP-at-Le-Mans-while-Dani-Pedrosa-suffers-injury-021243016180640 |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 September 2012 |first=Peter |last=Clifford |title=Superb Stoner wins in Le Mans |date=15 May 2011 |accessdate=1 January 2012 |work=[[Red Bull]] |publisher=Red Bull GmbH }}</ref> Fourth place followed in [[2011 Catalan motorcycle Grand Prix|Catalunya]], before another second place in [[2011 British motorcycle Grand Prix|Great Britain]], having started fifth and led the first few laps before being overtaken by teammate Stoner. Dovizioso extended his podium run to four races after third in the [[2011 Dutch TT|Netherlands]] and second at his home race at [[2011 Italian motorcycle Grand Prix|Mugello]].\n\nHe finished second for the fourth time in 2011, in the [[2011 Czech Republic motorcycle Grand Prix|Czech Republic]]; holding off pressure from Simoncelli.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.motorcyclenews.com/MCN/sport/sportresults/MotoGP/2011/August/aug1511-brno-motogp-andrea-dovizioso-thrilled-hold-off-marco-simoncelli/|work=[[Motor Cycle News]]|publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]]|first=Matthew|last=Birt|title=Andrea Dovizioso thrilled to hold off Marco Simoncelli|date=15 August 2011|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref> Two fifth places followed, before Dovizioso's only retirement of the season in [[2011 Aragon motorcycle Grand Prix|Aragon]], after crashing out. Dovizioso finished fifth in [[2011 Japanese motorcycle Grand Prix|Japan]], despite a ride-through penalty for jumping the start.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motogp/15140998.stm|first=Tom|last=Rostance|title=Dani Pedrosa claims dramatic MotoGP win in Japan|date=2 October 2011|accessdate=1 January 2012|work=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> Dovizioso finished third in [[2011 Australian motorcycle Grand Prix|Australia]] and [[2011 Valencian Community motorcycle Grand Prix|Valencia]], while the [[2011 Malaysian motorcycle Grand Prix|Malaysian race]] was cancelled after the death of Simoncelli in the first attempt to run the race.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motogp/15420069.stm|title=Marco Simoncelli dies after MotoGP crash in Sepang|work=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=23 October 2011|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe ended the season third behind [[Jorge Lorenzo]] and [[Casey Stoner]], but decided to move to the [[Tech 3|Tech3 Yamaha team]] for the {{MGP|2012}} season, alongside [[Cal Crutchlow]] on a one-year deal. Dovizioso moved to the team after rejecting the offer of a satellite Honda bike,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.motorcyclenews.com/MCN/sport/sportresults/MotoGP/2011/October/oct0811-dovizioso-signs-for-tech-3/|work=[[Motor Cycle News]]|publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]]|first=Matthew|last=Birt|title=Andrea Dovizioso shuns Honda for Tech 3 Yamaha|date=8 October 2011|accessdate=1 January 2012}}</ref> after Repsol Honda reverted to two bikes&nbsp;\u2013 for Stoner and Pedrosa&nbsp;\u2013 for the 2012 season.\n\n====Yamaha (2012)====\nDovizioso achieved top-five placings in each of his first three starts for Tech3, with fifth places in [[2012 Qatar motorcycle Grand Prix|Qatar]] and at [[2012 Spanish motorcycle Grand Prix|Jerez]], as well as a fourth place at the [[2012 Portuguese motorcycle Grand Prix|Portuguese Grand Prix]]. A seventh place followed at [[2012 French motorcycle Grand Prix|Le Mans]], before his first podium of the season&nbsp;\u2013 a third place&nbsp;\u2013 at the [[2012 Catalan motorcycle Grand Prix|Catalan Grand Prix]]. After missing out on points at the [[2012 British motorcycle Grand Prix|British Grand Prix]] due to a crash, Dovizioso finished third or fourth in each of the next six races \u2013 with four podiums \u2013 to maintain fourth place in the championship ahead of teammate Crutchlow.\n\nHe won the [[Supermoto]]-Race on SIC Supermoto Day together with Mauno Hermunen, a race in honor of the memory of the Italian racer [[Marco Simoncelli]], who also died in a race crash in 2011.\n\n====Ducati (2013\u2013present)====\n;2013\n[[File:Ducati D16GP13 Dovizioso DM 02.JPG|thumb|Ducati Desmosedici used by Dovizioso in the 2013 season]]\nFollowing [[Valentino Rossi]]'s move back to the factory Yamaha team, Dovizioso was signed by [[Ducati]] to replace Rossi in their factory team.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.motogp.com/en/news/2012/Andrea+Dovizioso+and+Ducati+together+beginning+in+2013|title=Andrea Dovizioso and Ducati together beginning in 2013|work=MotoGP.com|publisher=[[Dorna Sports]]|date=22 August 2012|accessdate=28 August 2012}}</ref> Dovizioso had a difficult season on an under-performing [[Ducati Desmosedici]], with a best place of fourth in wet conditions at the [[2013 French motorcycle Grand Prix|French Grand Prix]]. He ended the season eighth, behind [[Stefan Bradl]] and just ahead of teammate [[Nicky Hayden]].\n\n;2014\n[[File:Andrea DOVIZIOSO - Ducati Team - MotoGP 2014 - Le Mans (14217890902).jpg|left|thumb|Dovizioso at the [[2014 French motorcycle Grand Prix|2014 French Grand Prix]]]]\nDovizioso was joined at Ducati by his former Tech3 teammate [[Cal Crutchlow]], reuniting the riders that raced with Tech3 in {{MGP|2012}}. The season started in a positive way for Dovizioso, as he obtained three top-five results in the first four races, including a third place in the [[2014 Motorcycle Grand Prix of the Americas|Grand Prix of the Americas in Texas]] and claimed his first pole position with Ducati in [[2014 Japanese motorcycle Grand Prix|Japan]], his first pole position since {{MGP|2010}}. He ended the season fifth in the riders' championship.\n\n;2015\n[[File:Andrea Dovizioso-MotoGP-2015.JPG|thumb|right|Dovizioso at the [[2015 Catalan motorcycle Grand Prix|2015 Catalan Grand Prix.]]]]\nDovizioso remained at Ducati for a third successive season, where he was joined by fellow Italian rider, [[Andrea Iannone]], who moved from [[Pramac Racing]]. He took the first pole position of the season in [[2015 Qatar motorcycle Grand Prix|Qatar]], out-qualifying the rest of the field by 0.2 seconds.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dovizioso grabs sensational pole for Ducati|url=http://www.motogp.com/en/news/2015/03/29/dovizioso-grabs-sensational-pole-for-ducati/172720|date=29 March 2015|accessdate=6 April 2015|work=motogp.com|publisher=[[Dorna Sports]]}}</ref> In the race, he started well and battled with the factory [[Yamaha Motor Racing|Yamaha]]s of [[Valentino Rossi]] and [[Jorge Lorenzo]]. He finished in second place behind Rossi,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/motorsport/32109292|title=Valentino Rossi wins season opener in Qatar|work=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=29 March 2015|accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref> taking his first podium since the [[2014 Dutch TT|Dutch TT in June 2014]]. Teammate Iannone finished just behind in third place, giving the factory team their first double podium finish since the [[2010 Aragon motorcycle Grand Prix|2010 Aragon Grand Prix]]. In the following two races, he finished in second position. However, Dovizioso's form took a huge dip as he struggled with mechanical and crashes. Having scored 4 podiums from the first 5 races, he only added 1 more to his total for the rest of the season. He finished seventh in the championship.\n\n;2016\n[[File:2016 Andrea Dovizioso Ducati Desmosedici GP16.jpg|thumb|right|Dovisioso in 2016]]\nDovizioso started the season strongly in Qatar again, finishing 2nd, but was taken out by his teammate in the Argentine Grand Prix when he was 2nd, he ultimately limped over to finish 13th. He was taken out by Pedrosa in Austin while 3rd and had a water pump failure in Jerez to leave him well down the standings. Around this time it was announced that [[Jorge Lorenzo]] would be joining Ducati for 2017. A few weeks later Ducati announced that Dovizioso was to stay at Ducati to partner Lorenzo, while Iannone signed a contract with the Suzuki team. In the inaugural Austrian Grand Prix, where Ducati were favourites to win, he finished 2nd to his teammate Iannone, which left disappointed. However he finished the season strongly and took only his 2nd MotoGP win in the Malaysian Grand Prix ahead of [[Valentino Rossi]] and Jorge Lorenzo, his first win in 7 years. He finished the season fifth in the championship.\n\n;2017\nOnce again, Dovizioso started the season by finishing 2nd in Qatar, this time to new factory [[Yamaha]] rider, [[Maverick Vinales]]. He was taken out again in Argentina, this time by [[Aleix Espargaro]], before finishing 6th, 5th, and 4th in Austin, Jerez and Le Mans, however Ducati was pretty far behind the winner in those races. At the Italian Grand Prix, Dovizioso looked strong throughout practice and qualified 3rd behind Vinales and Rossi. He controlled the pace in the race, didn't let Vinales get away and ultimately passed him and opened up a gap to win the race, becoming the first Italian rider to win the Italian Grand Prix on a Ducati motorcycle. It was also his first dry MotoGP victory. 7 days later in Catalunya, he astonishingly managed to win the race again, having started 7th, ahead of Marquez, Pedrosa and his teammate. Back to back wins for Dovizioso put him only 7 points behind Vinales at the top of the standings, though he had talked down the possibility of a title fight. With Vinales crashing in Assen, he took the lead of the championship. However, a series of mediocre results in Assen, Sachsenring and Brno put him down to 3rd in the standings. He again took back-to-back wins in Austria and Great Britain, retaking the lead as Marquez retired due to blown engine. At the San Marino grand prix, he finished third and a 7th position at Aragon saw him lose the title lead to Marc Marquez once again. At the Japanese GP however, he took his fifth win of the season after passing Marquez on the final lap, reducing the deficit to 11 points. In the final round in [[2017 Valencian Community motorcycle Grand Prix|Valencia]] Dovizioso struggled,  qualifying only 9th. Despite getting a tow from teammate [[Jorge Lorenzo]], he ultimately crashed out of the race from 4th place with 5 laps remaining. He finished the season 2nd, losing the world championship battle to Marc Marquez, with total of 6 wins.\n\n;2018\n\nDovizioso took victory in the season opener in Qatar, beating [[Marc Marquez|Marc M\u00e1rquez]] to the line. He finished in sixth place at the second race of the season in Argentina. In total, he won 4 races in the [[2018 MotoGP season]], ultimately finishing runner-up to M\u00e1rquez for the second season in a row.\n\n;2019\n\nDovizioso won [[Qatar motorcycle Grand Prix|Qatar GP]] for a second time in a row and [[Austrian motorcycle Grand Prix|Austrian GP]] at [[Red Bull Ring]] with a final corner overtake on [[Marc M\u00e1rquez]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/motogp/news/ducati-protest-rejected-dovizioso-qatar/4350483/?filters%5Bdriver%5D%5B0%5D%5Btitle%5D=Andrea+Dovizioso&filters%5Bdriver%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D=4601|title=Ducati protest rejected, Dovizioso keeps Qatar win|website=www.motorsport.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/motogp/news/dovizioso-austria-win-ducati/4512933/?filters%5Bdriver%5D%5B0%5D%5Btitle%5D=Andrea+Dovizioso&filters%5Bdriver%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D=4601|title=Dovizioso: Austrian GP win manner will rejuvenate Ducati|website=www.motorsport.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> He suffered a large accident at [[British motorcycle Grand Prix|British GP]] where he was unable to avoid crashing [[Fabio Quartararo]] in front of him, running over the French rider's bike, sending him airborne and falling head-first to the ground heavily.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/motogp/news/dovizioso-hospitalised-huge-crash-silverstone/4519397/?filters%5Bdriver%5D%5B0%5D%5Btitle%5D=Andrea+Dovizioso&filters%5Bdriver%5D%5B0%5D%5Bvalue%5D=4601|title=Dovizioso hospitalised after temporary memory loss in crash|website=www.motorsport.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref> The accident caused him to have memory loss temporarily which he would fully recover from. He scored 9 podium finishes in the season, equalling his tally from the previous season. With 269 points \u2013 his highest career tally to date \u2013 Dovizioso finished 2nd to M\u00e1rquez for the third consecutive season.\n\n===Auto Racing career===\nDovizioso made his debut in auto racing when he participated in 2016 [[Lamborghini Super Trofeo]] at [[Circuit Ricardo Tormo]] round, driving a [[Lamborghini Hurac\u00e1n]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://speedsport.com/sports-cars/other-sports-cars/andrea-dovizioso-try-racing-lamborghini/|title=Andrea Dovizioso Entered In Super Trofeo World Final|last=Staff|first=SPEED SPORT|date=2016-11-28|website=SPEED SPORT|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-10}}</ref> He finished 4th in the first race in the Pro-Am class and won the second race.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://andreadovizioso.com/dovi2015/lamborghini-super-trofeo/?lang=en|title=Lamborghini Super Trofeo - Valencia circuit|date=2016-12-05|website=Andrea Dovizioso|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-10}}</ref>\n\nIt was announced in May 2019 that Dovizioso would take part in the [[Misano World Circuit Marco Simoncelli|Misano]] round of the [[2019 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|2019 DTM]] championship, driving an [[Audi RS5 Turbo DTM]] for [[W Racing Team|W Racing Team (WRT)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/news/motogp/motogps-dovizioso-race-dtm|author=Samarth Kanal|title=Moto GP's Dovizioso to race in DTM|work=Motor Sport Magazine|date=|accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref> He raced as a substitute driver for [[Pietro Fittipaldi]], who was briefly loaned to [[Team Rosberg]] from WRT as [[Jamie Green]] was absent due to appendicitis recovery. He qualified 15th for the first race and finished 12th, and started from 14th to finish 15th in the second race.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/dtm/news/dovizioso-audi-happier-misano-debut/4461930/|title=Dovizioso: Audi happier than me about Misano showing|website=www.motorsport.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Grand Prix motorcycle racing===\n\n====By season====\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Season\n!Class\n!Motorcycle\n!Team\n!Number\n!Race\n!Win\n!Podium\n![[Pole position|Pole]]\n!FLap\n!Pts\n!Plcd\n!WCh\n|- align=\"right\"\n! [[2001 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|2001]]\n| 125cc\n| [[Aprilia RS 125]]\n| RCGM Rubicone Corse\n| 51\n| 1\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| NC\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|- align=\"right\"\n! [[2002 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|2002]]\n| 125cc\n| [[Honda RS125R]]\n| [[Scot Racing Team]]\n| 34\n| 16\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 42\n| 16th\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|- align=\"right\"\n! [[2003 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|2003]]\n| 125cc\n| [[Honda RS125R]]\n| [[Scot Racing Team|Team Scot]]\n| 34\n| 16\n| 0\n| 4\n| 1\n| 0\n| 157\n| 5th\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|- align=\"right\"\n! [[2004 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|2004]]\n| 125cc\n| [[Honda RS125R]]\n| [[Scot Racing Team|Kopron Team Scot]]\n| 34\n| 16\n| 5\n| 11\n| 8\n| 3\n| 293\n|style=\"background:#FFFFBF;\"| '''1st'''\n| 1\n|- align=\"right\"\n! [[2005 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|2005]]\n| 250cc\n| [[Honda RS250RW]]\n| [[Scot Racing Team|Team Scot]]\n| 34\n| 16\n| 0\n| 5\n| 0\n| 1\n| 189\n|style=\"background:#FFDF9F;\"| '''3rd'''\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|- align=\"right\"\n! [[2006 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|2006]]\n| 250cc\n| [[Honda RS250RW]]\n|[[Scot Racing Team|Humangest Racing Team]]\n| 34\n| 16\n| 2\n| 11\n| 2\n| 4\n| 272\n|style=\"background:#DFDFDF;\"| '''2nd'''\n|&nbsp;\u2013\n|- align=\"right\"\n! [[2007 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|2007]]\n| 250cc\n| [[Honda RS250RW]]\n| [[Scot Racing Team|Kopron Team Scot]]\n| 34\n| 17\n| 2\n| 10\n| 2\n| 3\n| 260\n|style=\"background:#DFDFDF